Done. Second-pass revision of `src/blog/people/drafts/Jeff-Goldblum.md` is complete.

## What I changed

**Added a full section on The Fly (1986)** — the review's #1 note, and it was right. Seated it right after the brother's-death beat so the two reinforce each other. It's framed as the counter-evidence the thesis needed: a Seven who converts grief into "spiritual enhancement" gave his defining dramatic performance *as a man trapped in irreversible bodily decay with no reframe available*. That contradiction sharpens the piece instead of letting it off easy, and it doubles as the empathy payoff — grief he dodged in life, poured into a role.

**Landed the orphaned Geena Davis quote** inside that section and added the prior-marriage history (Patricia Gaul, then Davis). The "magical chapter" quote now pays off, and the fatherhood-at-62 beat carries more weight with two finished marriages behind it (added a callback there).

**Sharpened the "culture caught up" claim** — added his 90s A-list run (Jurassic Park '93, Independence Day '96) and the self-chosen 2000s quiet, so the renaissance reads as "drifted off and circled back," not "fame arrived late."

**Trimmed the jazz/Royal Albert Hall repeat** in the aging section — kept the emotionally loaded RAH mention in the brother section and the unique Cynthia Erivo "If I Only Had a Brain" payoff.

**Held the line** on the shower-glass motif (didn't add a callback, per the review's own caution) and kept the discipline thesis + persona empathy turn fully intact.

Ledgers and second-pass note updated; `blog-lint.sh` passes (0 fail).

